To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

According to this article (https://www.usar.army.mil/News/Article/3503100/army-counterintelligence-agents-train-in-puerto-rico-during-vigilant-defender-23/) published on the US Army Reserve official website, Vigilant Defender 23 took place between July 8-21, 2023 in Puerto Rico and involved the 752nd Military Intelligence Battalion (Counterintelligence), Interrogation Group, Military Intelligence Readiness Command. The article also notes that Army Reserve's 1st Mission Support Command supported training and that Col. Therefore, I request the following records:

3) Any internal or external organizational charts created during the lead up to Vigilant Defender 23 showing the command structure to be followed during the military training exercise.

4) Any attendance sheets produced during the course of the Vigilant Defender 23 military training exercise.

5) To the extent possible, any emails and associated attachments that mention Vigilant Defender 23.

To help limit the extent of the responsive documents, please limit search from Jan 1, 2023 through the time this request is processed. title: City of Cortez Economic Development - Rachael Marchbanks

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to request metadata relating to emails sent To, From, CC, or BCC the following accounts:

Rachael Marchbanks acting under 'grants' or other government email,  rmarchbanks@cortezco.gov, r_marchbanks@hotmail.com

Please provide me the following information for all emails sent, received, or cc'd into the City's emails from Jan. 1 2013 to Dec. 31, 2020 to/from/cc/bcc the above-listed accounts:

1. From address
2. To address
3. bcc addresses
4. cc addresses
5. Time
6. Date
7. Subject

Please note that I am not requesting the contents of each email. This is intended to lessen the burden as expressed by your city attorney. I am more than happy to provide documentation or tips for extracting this information from your mail server if needed. Google's Vault tooling should make this request straightforward to complete. E-mail metadata is trivially exportable from the IT infrastructure of any modern e-mail archiving or data retention system - such as Microsoft Outlook 365, Google, Datacove, etc. - and should be deliverable in a .CSV, .XLS, or other machine readable format. 

Please save yourself the step of transforming the CSV into a PDF for submittal. It will save effort and ultimately save taxpayer funds.

Please note that I am not requesting the contents of each email. E-mail metadata does not include the contents of the specified e-mails, thus do not need individual review for redaction.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not. If possible, I would request a waiver of all fees for searching or copying these records in that the disclosure of the requested information is in the public interest and will contribute significantly to the public’s understanding.

1. When filing this, please note which documents have already been paid for by another FOIA request, and I request that if those documents have already been screened, that they not be duplicated in cost.
2. When estimating cost of per page, please use the discretion allowed by the CORA statute to interpret the pages to be 11x17, multiple columns, and 4 point font. Since this is an electronic request, the print version should not be provided, but for purposes of cost estimation, please take into consideration that Cortez population is underprivileged, and extend the courtesy of pricing accordingly. Saving the step of transforming the CSV to PDF saves the City of Cortez time, saving the taxpayers of Cortez money. 
2a. The economic information for this judgment comes from the submission done by myself of Kauffman Indicators of Entrepreneurship for Montezuma County in comparison to many surrounding counties in Utah, New Mexico, and Colorado. As seen in page 8 of the publicly presented documents August 22, 2023, Montezuma County has compensation ranking at 39.27% within the Kaufmann Entrepreneurial Jobs Indicators, meaning that the policy taken by Cortez brings it into direct conflict with the interests of the people they impact should they price these or other electronic documents at a punitive rate.
2b. Because these documents are of the public interest, and the population is demonstrably disadvantaged, the policies of Cortez which require hundreds or thousands of dollars to achieve transparency could be construed poorly in civil proceedings, meaning that legal fees could ensue which would further penalize City of Cortez budgets. This is not my intent, therefore I state it up front that the best course of action would be to ensure that FOIA costs are not borne as specified.
3. Staff time to review these documents should reflect the actual costs, not the maximum costs allowed by CORA law, please recalculate these costs taking into consideration both the public interest as well as eliminating from your cost estimate any documents previously screened by staff.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely, 

Charles Jeter

communications.subject: RE: Texas Public Information Act Request: PUCT - PIA Q1 2024
communications.communication:
*** PUC Open Records Auto-Response. Please do not reply to this e-mail. ***
Thank you for submitting your open records request under the Public Information Act (PIA) to the Public Utility Commission of Texas (PUC). Your request has been forwarded to the PUC’s Public Information Coordinator. The Public Information Coordinator will address PIA requests in the order they are received, but in all cases within the time prescribed by law.
Time To Respond
We will promptly respond to your request by providing the requested information, informing you there is no responsive information, or notifying you all or a portion of the requested information falls under an exception to public disclosure and requires a ruling from the Office of the Attorney General (OAG). If the requested information does not fall under an exception to public disclosure but will take longer than 10 business days to produce, we will notify you of the date and time the information will be provided.
Request for Clarification
You can help us respond more quickly to your request by ensuring that your request is clear, specific, and requests only the information you wish to receive. We do our best to relate requests to the information we have and do not require records to be requested by their specific names, but if you know the specific name of the record you are requesting, it will help us respond more efficiently.
If your request is vague or overly broad, we may, in compliance with Texas Government Code § 552.222, request clarification in order to ensure we understand what information you are requesting.  Also, please keep in mind that we are not required under the PIA to create new information, do legal research, or answer questions.  See Open Records Decision Nos. 555 and 563 at https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/open-records-decisions.
Withholding Information
Although the PIA makes most government information available to the public, some exceptions exist. If we believe an exception applies, we will notify you that the information cannot be released and request a ruling from the OAG.
Costs
You may be charged for costs associated with responding to your request.  Personnel time is charged at $15 per hour, plus 20% of the personnel charge for overhead. There is also a charge of $0.10 per page, plus personnel time, if the request exceeds fifty pages, plus postage. These rates are set by the OAG.  You can find more information regarding costs associated with PIA requests here: https://texreg.sos.state.tx.us/public/readtac$ext.ViewTAC?tac_view=4&ti=1&pt=3&ch=70&rl=Y.
For more information regarding access to public information held by the PUC, please visit our website at https://www.puc.texas.gov/agency/about/contact/PIA.aspx.

You may also find more detailed information regarding the PIA in Texas Government Code Chapter 552 or on the OAG’s website at https://www.texasattorneygeneral.gov/open-government/members-public.

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI: Jack Hoover Aldrich
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

All Bureau records that might exist that mention or pertain to my grandfather Jack Hoover Aldrich (born 8-17-1920 - died 4-1-2014). Attached is his obituary. 

https://www.findagrave.com/memorial/127474305/jack-hoover-aldrich

My grandfather worked for American Car and Foundry (ACF Industries) in the state of New Mexico in the 1950s. According to my mother's recollection, my grandfather had to undergo a federal background check as his employment involved the transport of nuclear weapon materials by train car by the ACF corporation. My mother recalls federal law enforcement interviewing neighbors and friends in 1956, and then periodic checks afterwards. My grandfather also made repeated trips to the Philippines, where he met Imelda Marcos and other officials in the Philippine government. I am curious as to whether the bureau maintained a file on my grandfather. 

This request is for any and all records about my grandfather Jack Hoover Aldrich from any and all FBI offices, including HQ, field offices, legal attaches, and facilities that maintain records under the FBI’s control. Please conduct a search for any records on Aldrich held by the Albuquerque Field Office. According to a blog post I just read, it is important that I state the following: "As you know, your agency is required to search the records stored at NARA’s Washington Records Center in Suitland, MD, but still technically under your agency’s control. For more information see 36 CFR 1250.8" Please also conduct a physical search of records at NARA's Washington Records Center in Suitland, for any records or documents related to Aldrich.

Please include all potentially responsive materials, including but not limited to all communications, reports, inquiries, investigations, photographs, audio files, video files, memos, directives, etc. Please include all materials found in other subject files and all materials associated with any potentially-related names and any other known aliases, nicknames, code names, or any other identifying pseudonyms or references utilized by this agency. Please consult the Central Records System and records, the Electronic Surveillance (ELSUR) Data Management System and records, Microphone Surveillance (MISUR) records, Physical Surveillance (FISUR) records, Technical Surveillance (TESUR) records, and all available cross-reference indices, databases, and records, in addition to any other locations containing potentially-responsive materials related to Jack Hoover Aldrich.

Please include a search of any records or documents understood to be, or colloquially referred to as "COINTELPRO records" under the bureau's custody that could be construed as responsive to a request for records related to Jack Hoover Aldrich.

If the bureau cannot fulfill certain parts of this request or if certain portions must be redacted, please provide any reasonable segregable portion of a requested record after removing or redacting those portions claimed to be exempt, explain in writing the justification for redacting the record, indicate the extent of any redactions on the portion of the record which is made available or published and where technically feasible indicate on the redacted portion itself the specific exemption(s) claimed.

To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Reports show that USACE has been in contact with Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, son of Gov. Pedro Pierluisi Urrutia and owner of Silver Beach LLC, about a pier located within or near the boundaries of a property owned by Stay West Indied called "Mary Lee's by the Sea" in Guanica, Puerto Rico. The same reports show that their exists no  "maintenance permit" or a "nationwide permit" for the pier:

https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/gobierno/notas/hijo-del-gobernador-se-defiende-ante-falta-de-permisos-en-guanica-el-muelle-esta-fuera-de-la-propiedad/
https://www.elnuevodia.com/noticias/gobierno/notas/anthony-pierluisi-rojo-colaborara-con-investigaciones-sobre-supuestas-violaciones-ambientales-en-sus-propiedades/

Therefore, I request the following records:

1) Any communications, emails, text messages, and attachments exchanged between USACE and Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, employees of Silver Beach, LLC, and employees of Stay West Indies, the short-term rental company which Pierluisi is the general manager for, concerning properties owned or operated by Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC, and Stay West Indies

2) Any records concerning permits or the lack thereof of properties owned or operated by Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indies. Any records concerning permits or the lack thereof of piers located in or near properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indie.

3) Any records about an investigation into the lack of permits for properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indies. Any records concerning investigation into the lack of permits of piers located in or near properties owned or operated by either Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC and Stay West Indie.

4) Any communications, emails, text messages, and attachments between USACE and Puerto Rico Department of Natural and Environmental Resources (DRNA, by their Spanish acronym) concerning Anthony Pierluisi Rojo, Silver Beach, LLC, and Stay West Indies.

Keywords: "Anthony Pierluisi," "Pierluisi Rojo," "Pierluisi," "DRNA," "Stay West Indies," "Silver Beach,  LLC," "Silver Beach,"  "Guanica," "Mary Lee's by the Sea," "Mary Lee's."

To help aid in your search, I believe that employees of Stay West Indies' email addresses end with "@staywestindies.com"

This records request is for records between January 1, 2020 and the time this request is processed.  

This record is not being made for commercial purposes. I am a freelance journalist and records retrieved from this request will be used in the course of reporting about Puerto Rico's beaches and the archipelago's permits office.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Carlos Berríos Polanco
